    {
      "date": "2026-08-31",
      "title": "No Turning Back (written by Bro. Lawrence Tong)",
      "passage": "Luke9:57-62",
      "passageText": "57 As they were going along the road, someone said to him, “I will follow you wherever you go.” 58 And Jesus said to him, “Foxes have holes, and birds of the air have nests, but the Son of Man has nowhere to lay his head.” 59 To another he said, “Follow me.” But he said, “Lord, let me first go and bury my father.” 60 And Jesus said to him, “Leave the dead to bury their own dead. But as for you, go and proclaim the kingdom of God.” 61 Yet another said, “I will follow you, Lord, but let me first say farewell to those at my home.” 62 Jesus said to him, “No one who puts his hand to the plow and looks back is fit for the kingdom of God.”",
      "article": "There are moments in life when a single decision changes everything.\nIn Luke 9, Jesus encounters three people who express a desire to follow Him. Yet each faces a choice. Would they allow competing priorities, personal attachments, or future uncertainties to stand in the way of wholehearted discipleship?\nJesus concludes with these challenging words:\n“No one who puts a hand to the plow and looks back is fit for service in the kingdom of God.”\nAt first glance, His words seem demanding. Yet behind them is an invitation—to a life centered on Him.\nNearly forty-eight years ago, I said yes to following Jesus through missionary service with Operation Mobilization. There were seasons of financial pressure, difficult decisions, and uncertain paths ahead. Yet if I were given the opportunity to begin again, I would make the same choice.\nWhy?\nBecause I have discovered that Jesus is worthy.\nThe world constantly invites us to look back—to what we might have achieved, accumulated, or experienced had we chosen a different path. Jesus invites us to look forward. He calls us to trust Him and believe that no sacrifice made for His sake is ever wasted.\nWhether Jesus leads us across the street or across the world, His invitation remains the same: “Follow Me.” When we fix our eyes on Him, we discover that the greatest joy in life is not found in what we leave behind, but in the One we follow.\nFor those who choose to follow Him, there is no better way to live—and no reason to turn back.",
